Using the coefficients from your model, calculate the wage percentage of male income for Sales and Office occupations in 2015.

y = mx+b(coiefficient)

Si = -307 + 0.192(2015) + 3.33(1) = 83.21

Wage percentage of male income for Sales and Office Occ. in 2015 is 83.21%

Now calculate the wage percentage of male income for Service occupations on 2016.

Si = -307 + 0.192(2016) + 6.08(1) = 86.15

Wage percentage of male income for Service occupations in 2016 is 86.15%

Question 4

Given that we have the ability to add interactions to models - i.e. to have slopes vary across categories -, why would we choose to build a model that assumes parallel trends?

We would want to build a model that assumes parralel trends as the relationship between major categories, year, and wage percentage of males calls for a more complex model.

Wage percentage of male has a positive linear relationship to both year and percentage of females in the workspace, but it is quite small. Percentage of females in the workforce also has a positive linear relationship with year and wage percentage of males, but also quite small.

multiple_fit <- lm(percent_female ~ wage_percent_of_male + year,
                   data = gen_employment)
tidy(multiple_fit)
## # A tibble: 3 × 5
##   term                 estimate std.error statistic   p.value

When conditional on the percentage of females in the workforce, the y-intercept is -81.23 and the wage percentage of males is 0.29. I expected a small number, but definetly larger than the previous values we got in previous questions for the wage percentage of males because it was now contingent on the percentage of females.

Question 6

R-squared is the part of the dependent variable that can be determined by the independent variable, hence its name “the coefficient of determination”.

simple_glanced <- glance(simple_fit)
simple_glanced$r.squared
## [1] 0.0005778711
multiple_glanced <- glance(multiple_fit)
multiple_glanced$r.squared
## [1] 0.01242971

The r-squared for the simple_fit is 0.00058 and the r-squared for the multiple fit is 0.01243, which means that observed outcomes are replicated better/more accuratelt by the multiple fit model than the simple fit model.

Warning sign:

random_numbers <- rnorm(n = nrow(gen_employment), 
                        mean = 0, 
                        sd = 4)
gen_employment$random_noise <- random_numbers

# New model 
random_fit <- lm(wage_percent_of_male ~ year + percent_female + random_noise, data = gen_employment)
random_glanced <- glance(random_fit)
random_glanced$r.squared
## [1] 0.01316706

Based on this r-squared, the random-fit model that the observed outcomes are replicated better than both the multiple fit and simple fit models.
